Nelson,

I think I prefer the cleanness of this way to test interfaces by Eric
George,
http://www.placebosoft.com/abstract-test.html

Given the method you describe below, the test class will become rather
large quite quickly each time a new implementing class is tested.
Eric&#39;s way allows a new unit test class to be added, therefore being
more modular.

Andy.

--
Andrew Beacock
Lammtara


&gt; -----Original Message-----
&gt; From: Nelson [mailto:nervousxians@...] 
&gt; Sent: 21 September 2003 23:25
&gt; To: junit@yahoogroups.com
&gt; Subject: [junit] Concept of testing classes that implement Interfaces?
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Given that all classes {C} implement interface X, it would 
&gt; prolly be most logical to define test methods which all 
&gt; assert the successful functionality for an instance of every 
&gt; class in {C}. This way, we can be  sure all implementations 
&gt; correctly work at runtime while reusing as much test code as possible.
&gt; 
&gt; For example since classes {ArrayList, SortedSet} both 
&gt; implement interface Collection, the same tests can be applied 
&gt; to both :
&gt;    test_add()
&gt;    test_remove()
&gt;    ...etc
&gt; 
&gt; Here is my plan on implementing this:
&gt; 
&gt; I will have class AllImplTest extends TestCase which will 
&gt; have protected methods for each type of test. Using the 
&gt; Collections as an
&gt; example:
&gt; 
&gt; class AllImplTest extends TestCase
&gt; {
&gt;     protected boolean test_add(final Collection inCollection)
&gt;     {
&gt; 
&gt;     }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; The test_add will essentially test the inCollection to see if 
&gt; can successfully add an element.
&gt; 
&gt; Then, I will have separate public methods to test each know 
&gt; implementation of the Collection interface eg
&gt;  
&gt;     public test_add_ArrayList()
&gt;     {
&gt;         ArrayList locArrayList=new ArrayList();
&gt; 
&gt;          boolean bSuccess=test_add(locArrayList);
&gt; 
&gt;          assertTrue(bSuccess);
&gt;     }
&gt;   
&gt; This works great, but the only catch is, for every different 
&gt; type of implementation that is created, i&#39;d have to add the 
&gt; test, no biggie though.
&gt; 
&gt; What do you guys think about this?
